1. What is stack?
-----------------

A stack is an STL container adaptor that follows the
LIFO (Last In First Out) principle.

The last element inserted is the first one removed.

Example:

push(10)
push(20)
push(30)

Top -> 30

pop()

30 removed first

-----------------------------------------

2. Explain LIFO.
----------------

LIFO = Last In First Out

Example:

Stack:

Bottom
------
10
20
30
------
Top

Last inserted = 30

First removed = 30

Real-life Example:

Stack of plates

Last plate placed on top is removed first.

-----------------------------------------

3. How is std::stack implemented internally?
--------------------------------------------

std::stack is a container adaptor.

It does not store elements itself.

Instead it uses another STL container internally.

Default:

deque

Example:

stack<int> st;

Internally:

deque<int> d;

Interview Answer:

std::stack is implemented as a container adaptor that uses another container (deque by default) to store elements and exposes only stack operations.

-----------------------------------------

4. Default underlying container of stack?
-----------------------------------------

Default Container:

deque

Example:

stack<int> st;

Internally:

stack<int, deque<int>>

Alternative containers:

stack<int, vector<int>>
stack<int, list<int>>

Interview Q:
What is the default container used by stack?

Answer:
deque.

